The defendant Zachary George Senner was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Mistreatment of Animals/Cause Death [Modifiers: Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 951.02.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:

The Court sentenced the defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT of 54 MONTHS in the Wisconsin State Prisons, credit for 53 days time served.  CONFINEMENT of 30 MONTHS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 24 MONTHS with the following conditions:

- Court ordered fine of $1000.00- Cash bail to apply to the fine. 
- The Court ordered that all court costs, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.
-Pay all costs, assessments and victim/witness surcharges.
-Provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs; DNA surcharge.
-Complete AODA Assessment and comply with any treatment required.
-Defendant may not own or train any animals for 5 YEARS.

The defendant is advised as a convicted felon he may not carry or possess any firearms/body armor.
The court advises the defendant that voting privileges are suspended during the length of this sentence.
The defendant is given a written explanation of the determinate sentence, and advised of his appeal rights by defense counsel.
The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.   
The defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.   

Defendant is remanded.
